10 years training model¶

  • Split the data from 1990-1999 to train the 10 years model.
  • Split the data from 2000-2009 to test the 3 years prediction from 2000-2002.
In [ ]:
# Train-Test Split
train_10_years = df_monthly['1990':'1999']
test_10_years = df_monthly['2000':'2009']
  • Use Box-Jenkins Method for identifiction, estimation and model diagnostic.
  • Identification: make the data stationary and find the number of differencing, d.
  • Use Statsmodel function to perform Augmented Dickey-Fuller (ADF) test on the time series datasets.
  • P-value > 0.05: Fail to reject the null hypothesis (H0), the data has a unit root and is non-stationary.
  • P-value <= 0.05: Reject the null hypothesis (H0), the data does not have a unit root and is stationary.
  • First round of differencing, p-value = 0.44 > 0.05 fail to reject the null hypothesis.
In [ ]:
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller

# Check for Stationarity
result = adfuller(train_10_years['Mean Temperature (°C)'])
print('ADF Test on Original 10-Year Data:')
print(f'ADF Statistic: {result[0]}')
print(f'p-value: {result[1]}')

ADF Test on Original 10-Year Data:
ADF Statistic: -1.6798983157128884
p-value: 0.4414980902572134
  • Re-run the ADF test to confirm stationarity as the p-value is high.
  • Second round of differencing, p-value = 0.0001 < 0.05 reject the null hypothesis.
In [ ]:
# Re-run the ADF test to confirm stationarity.
train_10_years_diff = train_10_years['Mean Temperature (°C)'].diff().dropna()
result = adfuller(train_10_years_diff)
print('\nADF Test on Differenced 10-Year Data:')
print(f'ADF Statistic: {result[0]}')
print(f'p-value: {result[1]}')

ADF Test on Differenced 10-Year Data:
ADF Statistic: -4.5001669992850255
p-value: 0.00019650331816004998
  • Create ACF & PACF plots to identify the model type and value of p and q.
  • Both plots are cuts off after lag 1.
  • However, there is a significant spike at lag 12.
  • The regular lag is the sign of seasonality.
  • Therefore, it is a SARIMA model.
In [ ]:
# To identify the p and q orders from ACF and PACF plots
from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf, plot_pacf

fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(2,1, figsize=(12,8))
plot_acf(train_10_years_diff, lags=24, ax=ax1)
plot_pacf(train_10_years_diff, lags=24, ax=ax2)
plt.show()
print("ACF shows a strong spike at lag 12, confirming yearly seasonality.")

ACF shows a strong spike at lag 12, confirming yearly seasonality.
  • Estimation:
  • Use for loop with try except to manual search and store the values of different p, q, P, Q, AIC and BIC in the DataFrame.
  • Sort the results to find the model with the lowest (best) AIC or BIC.
  • AIC is better at choosing predictive models
  • BIC is better at choosing good explanatory model
  • Therefore, use the values of p, q, P, Q with lowest AIC value.
In [ ]:
# Estimation

from statsmodels.tsa.statespace.sarimax import SARIMAX

p_range = range(0, 3) # Non-seasonal AR order
d = 1                 # Non-seasonal differencing
q_range = range(0, 3) # Non-seasonal MA order

P_range = range(0, 3) # Seasonal AR order
D = 1                 # Seasonal differencing
Q_range = range(0, 3) # Seasonal MA order
m = 12                # Seasonal period (monthly data)

# Create a list to store the results
order_aic_bic = []

# Loop over all non-seasonal and seasonal order combinations
for p in p_range:
    for q in q_range:
        for P in P_range:
            for Q in Q_range:
                try:
                    order = (p, d, q)
                    seasonal_order = (P, D, Q, m)

                    # Fit the SARIMAX model
                    model = SARIMAX(train_10_years['Mean Temperature (°C)'],
                                    order=order,
                                    seasonal_order=seasonal_order)
                                    # enforce_stationarity=False,
                                    # enforce_invertibility=False)

                    results = model.fit()

                    # Add order and scores to the list
                    order_aic_bic.append((p, q, P, Q, results.aic, results.bic))
                    print(f"SARIMA({p},{d},{q})({P},{D},{Q})[{m}] - AIC:{results.aic:.2f}")

                except:
                    # If a model fails to fit, we print None for its scores
                    print(f"SARIMA({p},{d},{q})({P},{D},{Q})[{m}] - Failed to fit")
                    order_aic_bic.append((p, q, P, Q, None, None))
                    continue

# Make DataFrame of model order and AIC/BIC scores
order_df = pd.DataFrame(order_aic_bic, columns=['p', 'q', 'P', 'Q', 'aic', 'bic'])

# Sort by AIC to find the best model for prediction
print("Sorted by AIC:")
print(order_df.sort_values('aic'))

  • Model diagnostics:
  • To check how good the final model is.
  • If a model is good, its residuals should behave like white Gaussian noise
  • Residuals plot: No obvious patterns or trends.
  • Histogram plus estimated density: The histogram shows us the measured distribution. The model is good because the orange line and green line are almost the same.
  • Normal Q-Q: To show how the distribution of the model residuals compares to a normal distribution. The residuals are normally distributed because almost all the points lie along the red line.
  • Correlogram: It is just an ACF plot of the residuals. 95% of the correlations for lag greater than zero should not be significant. If there is significant correlation in the residuals, it means that there is information in the data that our model hasn't captured.
  • Summary statistics:
    1. Prob(Q): Tests if residuals are uncorrelated. P-value > 0.05 is good.
    1. Prob(JB): Tests if residuals are normally distributed. P-value > 0.05 is good.

# Forecasting and Evaluation
from statsmodels.tsa.statespace.sarimax import SARIMAX
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error

test_3_years = df_monthly['2000':'2002']
one_step_forecast_obj_3_years = best_results_manual.get_prediction(start='2000-01-31', end='2002-12-31')

# Confidence intervals
mean_forecast_3_step = one_step_forecast_obj_3_years.predicted_mean
conf_int_3_step = one_step_forecast_obj_3_years.conf_int()
lower_limits = conf_int_3_step.iloc[:, 0]
upper_limits = conf_int_3_step.iloc[:, 1]

# Calculate MAE
mae_one_step_3 = mean_absolute_error(test_3_years['Mean Temperature (°C)'], mean_forecast_3_step)  # test_3_years here is from 200001.csv to 200212.csv data
print(f"\nMean Absolute Error (One-Step-Ahead, 3-Year Model): {mae_one_step_3:.2f}")

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 6))
plt.plot(test_10_years.index, test_10_years['Mean Temperature (°C)'], label='Observed')
plt.plot(mean_forecast_3_step.index, mean_forecast_3_step, color='red', label='One-Step-Ahead Forecast')
plt.fill_between(mean_forecast_3_step.index, lower_limits, upper_limits, color='pink', alpha=0.5)
plt.title('One-Step-Ahead Forecast vs Actuals (2000-2002)')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Mean Absolute Error (One-Step-Ahead, 3-Year Model): 0.34
  • The mean absolute error of predict for 3 years (0.34) is lower than predict for 10 year (0.48).
  • This maybe because of the mean temperature of last 7 years have changed.
